&lt;p&gt;
The numbers $169$ and $961$ are both perfect squares of prime numbers. Interestingly, $169$ is the reverse of $961$.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
We define a number as a &lt;dfn&gt;reversible prime square&lt;/dfn&gt; under the following conditions:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The number is not a palindrome, and&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;It is the perfect square of a prime number, and&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The reverse of this number is also a perfect square of a prime number.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
Given that $169$ and $961$ are not palindromes, they both qualify as reversible prime squares.
&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
Determine the aggregate of the initial $50$ reversible prime squares.
